  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the difference between strong and eventual consistency? Give scenarios where each is appropriate.",
  "response_text": "Strong consistency and eventual consistency are concepts used in distributed systems to ensure data consistency across multiple nodes.\n\nStrong consistency, also known as immediate consistency, guarantees that all reads will return the most recent write, regardless of the location of the reader or the writer. This means that if a write operation is performed on one node, all other nodes will reflect the same change immediately. This is achieved by using techniques like two-phase commit or locking.\n\nScenario for strong consistency: A banking application where real-time updates of account balances are crucial. If a user transfers money from one account to another, both accounts' balances should reflect the change instantly, ensuring the user has an accurate view of their funds at all times.\n\nEventual consistency, on the other hand, does not guarantee that all nodes will reflect the same data at the same time. Instead, it ensures that if no new writes occur, all nodes will eventually converge to the same state. This is achieved by using techniques like the eventual consistency algorithm (VECTOR) or the optimistic concurrency control (OCC).\n\nScenario for eventual consistency: A social media platform where users can post updates. If a user posts a status update, it may take some time for all users to see the update due to the large number of users and the need for efficiency. However, eventually, all users will see the update as long as no new writes occur.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
